H2365.name: An Act to improve the Commonwealth’s economy with a strong minimum wage and a strong tipped minimum wage
H2365.description: Raises minimum wage to $15 by 2021 and indexes it to inflation. Ensures that tipped employees’ wages plus tips equal the new strengthened minimum wage.

S1004.name: An Act to improve the Commonwealth’s economy with a strong minimum wage and a strong tipped minimum wage
S1004.description: Raises minimum wage to $15 by 2021 and indexes it to inflation. Ensures that tipped employees’ wages plus tips equal the new strengthened minimum wage.

H2172.name: An Act establishing a paid family and medical leave insurance program
H2172.description: Makes employees eligible for job-protected paid leave to recover from a serious illness or injury, to care for a seriously ill or injured family member, or to care for a new child.

S1048.name: An Act establishing a paid family and medical leave insurance program
S1048.description: Makes employees eligible for job-protected paid leave to recover from a serious illness or injury, to care for a seriously ill or injured family member, or to care for a new child.

S81.name: An Act promoting housing and sustainable development
S81.description: Upgrades state’s zoning laws to encourage more affordable housing and transit-oriented, walkable development, and promotes inclusionary zoning  practices.

H2987.name: An Act establishing Medicare for All in Massachusetts
H2987.description: Establishes a single payer system, in which the state provides health care to all residents as a right.

S619.name: An Act establishing Medicare for All in Massachusetts
S619.description: Establishes a single payer system, in which the state provides health care to all residents as a right.

S223.name: An Act modernizing the Foundation Budget for the 21st century
S223.shorthand_title: Robust and equitable K-12 public ed funding
S223.description: Requires the state to implement the recommendations of the the 2015 Foundation Budget Review Commission on K-12 education.

H633.name: An Act making public higher education in Massachusetts free for residents of the state
H633.description: Establishes free college tuition and fees for all Massachusetts residents.

S681.name: An Act promoting access to debt-free public higher education
S681.description: Establishes free college (community college and/or state university) education for students of all families earning $200,000 a year or less, covering tuition, fees, housing, and transportation costs.

H2308.name: An Act for justice reinvestment
H2308.shorthand_title: Justice reform & reinvestment (or "jobs and education, not jails and incarceration")
H2308.description: Enacts comprehensive justice reform, complementing reductions in sentencing with jobs training, youth jobs, and pre-apprenticeship programs.

S791.name: An Act for justice reinvestment
S791.shorthand_title: Justice reform & reinvestment (or "jobs and education, not jails and incarceration")
S791.description: Enacts comprehensive justice reform, complementing reductions in sentencing with jobs training, youth jobs, and pre-apprenticeship programs.

H741.name: An Act to eliminate mandatory minimum sentences related to drug offenses
H741.description: Restores judicial discretion in sentencing for nonviolent drug charges, reducing the economic and social costs of extended prison terms.

S819.name: An Act to eliminate mandatory minimum sentences related to drug offenses
S819.description: Restores judicial discretion in sentencing for nonviolent drug charges, reducing the economic and social costs of extended prison terms.

H3269.name: An Act to protect the civil rights and safety of all Massachusetts residents (“Safe Communities Act”)
H3269.description: Prohibits the use of state resources for mass deportations or deportation raids, limits local and state police collaboration with federal immigration agents, and prohibits state support for Muslim registry.

S1305.name: An Act to protect the civil rights and safety of all Massachusetts residents (“Safe Communities Act”)
S1305.description: Prohibits the use of state resources for mass deportations or deportation raids, limits local and state police collaboration with federal immigration agents, and prohibits state support for Muslim registry.

H2359.name: An Act to reduce the criminalization of poverty
H2359.description: Eliminates or reduces numerous fees, such as parole supervision, and ensures indigent residents are not jailed or given unreasonable fees simply because they struggle to pay court-related fines.

S777.name: An Act to reduce the criminalization of poverty
S777.description: Eliminates or reduces numerous fees, such as parole supervision, and ensures indigent residents are not jailed or given unreasonable fees simply because they struggle to pay court-related fines.

H536.name: An Act relative to advancing contraceptive coverage and economic security in our state (ACCESS)
H536.description: Updates MA’s contraceptive coverage equity law to require insurance carriers to provide all contraceptive methods without a copay.

S499.name: An Act relative to advancing contraceptive coverage and economic security in our state (ACCESS)
S499.description: Updates MA’s contraceptive coverage equity law to require insurance carriers to provide all contraceptive methods without a copay.

H 2091.name: An Act automatically registering eligible voters and enhancing safeguards against fraud
H 2091.description: Modernizes voter registration by automatically registering citizens who interact with government agencies ("opt-out" instead of "opt-in") and ensures that such information is handled in a secure fashion.

S373.name: An Act automatically registering eligible voters and enhancing safeguards against fraud
S373.description: Modernizes voter registration by automatically registering citizens who interact with government agencies ("opt-out" instead of "opt-in") and ensures that such information is handled in a secure fashion.

S1880.name: An Act creating 21st Century Massachusetts clean energy jobs
S1880.description: Establishes a climate adaptation and management program, sets greenhouse gas reduction targets for 2030 and 2040, accelerates the state’s Renewable Portfolio Standard (RPS), and increases commitment to offshore wind.

H2706.name: An Act relative to solar power and the green economy
H2706.description: Accelerates the state’s commitment to clean energy (RPS increase) and sets 25% by 2030 solar target.

S1846.name: An Act relative to solar power and the green economy
S1846.description: Accelerates the state’s commitment to clean energy (RPS increase) and sets 25% by 2030 solar target.

H3400.name: An Act clarifying authorities and responsibilities of the Department of Public Utilities
H3400.description: Holds gas companies to a high standard with regards to new infrastructure and prevents massive public subsidy of new interstate gas pipelines.

S1847.name: An Act clarifying authorities and responsibilities of the Department of Public Utilities
S1847.description: Holds gas companies to a high standard with regards to new infrastructure and prevents massive public subsidy of new interstate gas pipelines.

H1726.name: An Act to promote green infrastructure, reduce greenhouse gas emissions, and create jobs
H1726.description: Enacts revenue-positive carbon pricing. 80% is rebated to residents while 20% is invested in green infrastructure, with a carve-out for low-income communities.

S1821.name: An Act combating climate change
S1821.description: Enacts revenue-neutral carbon pricing. Every state resident receives an equal rebate, and employers get rebates based on their number of employees.

5.description: Vote was on giving pay increases to the Senate President, Speaker of the House, judges, the governor, and other constitutional officers; raising stipends to appointed committee chairs and select other legislative leaders; and increasing the number of legislators eligible for stipends. The bill would further centralize power in the already powerful House Speaker and create a more hierarchical and less democratic Legislature. The bill received little notice and no public hearing, and was fast-tracked while many vital priorities to the Commonwealth languish in perpetuity.
5.title: An Act Further Regulating the Compensation of Public Officials

19.description: Vote was on requiring committee roll call votes to be posted on the Clerks’ websites. This is current practice in the Senate, but not the House.
19.title: Committee Roll Calls on Website

26.description: Vote was on reducing the state income tax to 5.0% (from its current 5.1%) by the effective date of 2016’s Question 4 to further study,
26.title: Ballot Question Equity Amendment

30.description: Vote was on sending an amendment to reduce the sales tax from 6.25% to 5.00% to further study, thereby dispensing with it. The amendment would have drained the state of much-needed revenue.
30.title: Further to An Amendment to Restore the 5% Sales Tax

41.description: Vote was on dispensing with an amendment that would prevent mixed-status immigrant families from living in public housing.
41.title: Further to "Securing Public Housing"

43.description: Vote was on sending to further study an amendment that would deny cash benefits to individuals who use such benefits in non-bordering states, thereby dispensing with it.
43.title: Further Amendment to Cash Assistance Expenditures

67.description: Vote was on sending the Fair Share amendment, which would impose a 4% surtax on income above $1 million and allocate the revenue to a designated education and transportation fund, to the 2018 ballot.
67.title: Fair Share Amendment

69.description: Vote was on amending the House's marijuana regulation bill to prevent cities and towns that pass local bans on marijuana from receiving substance treatment and prevention funds from the bill, creating an incentive to prevent the concentration of marijuana stores in urban areas alone.
69.title: Funds Directed only to Participating Communities

70.keyword: Criminal Justice, Racial Equity, Gender Equity, Drug War
70.description: Vote was on promoting the inclusion of women- and minority-owned businesses in the cannabis industry, encouraging the full participation of communities that had been disproportionately harmed by the war on drugs, sealing marijuana offenses that are no longer considered a crime, and other steps toward racial equity.
70.title: Consolidated B: Equity Amendment
70.keywords: Criminal Justice, Racial Equity, Gender Equity, Drug War

72.description: Vote was on significantly rewriting the language on marijuana legalization passed via Question 4 on the 2016 ballot. The bill would more than double the tax on marijuana, creating the conditions for black market to flourish; eliminate the ability of voters to have a direct say over local marijuana policy; and create new law enforcement agencies with broad and poorly defined powers -- while weakening core equity provisions.
72.title:
An Act to ensure the public health and safety of patient and consumer 
access to medical and adult use of marijuana in the Commonwealth

77.description: Vote was on the conference committee version of the Question 4 redraft (marijuana legalization), which remained faithful to the spirit of the original ballot
77.title: An act to ensure safe access to marijuana

78.description: Vote was on freezing employer contributions to the unemployment insurance trust fund, a $334 million giveaway that depletes an already underfunded program (proposed in an attempt to sweeten a tax on employers whose workers get coverage from MassHealth).
78.title: Unemployment Insurance Trust Fund

79.description: Vote was on Governor Baker’s proposal to drop 100,000 low-income parents and 40,000 other adults off MassHealth, a proposal which would subject such individuals to higher premiums and a loss of dental coverage and other vital benefits.
79.title: An Act Further Regulating Employer Contributions to Health Care

276.description: Vote was on committing Massachusetts to the greenhouse gas emissions reduction goals laid out in the Paris Climate Agreement. The bill would make Massachusetts a “non-party stakeholder” to the agreement and allow state officials to document their emissions reductions efforts through a UN-developed online data-gathering tool.
276.title: An Act relative to Massachusetts participation in the Paris Climate Agreement's Green House Gas Emission Standards

279.description: Vote was on updating MA’s contraceptive coverage equity law to require insurance carriers to provide all contraceptive methods without a copay.
279.title: An Act relative to advancing contraceptive coverage and economic security in our state (ACCESS)

285.description: Vote was on upholding the ruling of the Chair that an amendment to give local law enforcement authority to hold people in custody based on a detainer from ICE was out of order. The amendment would have violated the constitutional rights of the immigrants being held.
285.title: Detention Request -- Upholding the Ruling of the Chair

286.description: Vote was on sending to further study (i.e., dispensing with) an amendment to manslaughter charges for anyone providing a drug that results in death, which would have made such individuals less likely to call for emergency medical help in such situations.
286.title: Further amdt to Penalty or heroin trafficking resulting in death

287.description: Vote was on upholding the ruling of the Chair that the amendment to expand the state’s wiretapping law and curtail privacy rights was out of order.
287.title: Point of order -- Wiretap

290.description: Vote was on allowing for the expungement of certain juvenile records after 7 years in the case of a felony and after 3 years in the case of a misdemeanor, enabling people to have second chance and better reintegrate into the community.
290.title: Juvenile expungement

291.description: Vote was on raising the threshold at which larceny (theft) is treated as a felony, rather than a misdemeanor, from $250 to $1,000. The current felony-larceny threshold in Massachusetts is the third lowest in the country.
291.title: Felony larceny threshold

292.description: Vote was on expanding the witness intimidation statute to cover more people and transactions and have higher penalties, opening up possibilities for police and prosecutorial abuse given the lack of requirement for an empirical foundation for such charges.
292.title: Witness intimidation

294.description: Vote was on raising the felony threshold for malicious destruction of property from property valued over $250 to damage valued over $1,000 and changes the fine calculating factor from $3000 or three times the value of the property to $3000 or three times the value of the damage caused to the property
294.title: Malicious destruction of property

295.description: Vote was on sending to further study (i.e., dispensing with) an amendment to manslaughter charges for anyone providing a drug that results in death, which would have made such individuals less likely to call for emergency medical help in such situations.
295.title: Further amdt to Drug Distribution Causing Death

320.description: Vote was on passing the conference committee criminal justice reform bill that, while imperfect, took significant steps toward curbing mass incarceration in Massachusetts
320.title: An Act Relative to Criminal Justice Reform

334.description: Vote was on a budget amendment to allow state and local law enforcement agencies to arrest and hold without a warrant a person suspected of immigration violations, which would violate basic constitutional rights and make communities less safe.
334.title: Warrantless arrests and holds

335.description: Vote was to table ("send to further study)" an amendment to block local aid to communities that have adopted ordinances or policies restricting local police from cooperating with federal ICE (Immigration and Customs Enforcement) agents.
335.title: Tabling an amendment to block local aid to sanctuary cities

349.description: Vote was on reauthorizing a corporate tax giveaway for the biotech industry, including provisions increasing the amount  of money available each year for industry tax incentives and thus draining much-needed revenue.
349.title: An act providing continued investment in the life sciences industry

352.keyword: Gun Violence, Public Safety, Public Health
352.description: Vote was on amending the Extreme Risk Protection Order (ERPO) bill to require the state to provide a mental health assessment of an individual who receives an ERPO within 48 hours and, if deemed necessary, to create a mental health program for that individual. The amendment aimed to stigmatize mental illness and evade the root issue of gun violence.
352.title: Mental Health Counseling
352.keywords: Gun Violence, Public Safety, Public Health

356.keyword: Gun Violence, Public Safety, Public Health
356.description: Vote was on amending the ERPO (Extreme Risk Protection Order) bill to increase the evidentiary standard for approving an ERPO from “the preponderance of evidence” to “clear and convincing evidence," an attempt to nullify the bill’s ability to prevent mass shootings or suicides.
356.title: Increasing the standard to ‘clear and convincing evidence’ for the Courts to approve an ERPO petition
356.keywords: Gun Violence, Public Safety, Public Health

359.keyword: Gun Violence, Public Safety, Public Health
359.description: Vote was on creating a kind of court order (Extreme Risk Protection Order, or ERPO) to temporarily restrict a person's access to guns because they pose a significant danger to themselves or others, which can be requested by family members and law enforcement. Empowering family members, who are able to see early warning signs, to act in this way can prevent gun violence, whether mass shooting or suicide.
359.title: An Act Relative to Firearms (ERPO)
359.keywords: Gun Violence, Public Safety, Public Health

374.description: Vote was on amending the House’s health care reform bill to require surgeons intending to operate on multiple patients at once to seek informed consent of the patients. Recent studies have shown that double-booked surgeries put patients at extra risks.
374.title: Informed Consent for Surgical Procedures

377.description: Vote was on moving forward the “Grand Bargain” deal on the $15 minimum wage, paid family and medical leave, and sales tax holiday ballot initiatives before the Raise Up Massachusetts coalition, the grassroots coalition of community, faith, and labor groups and leaders behind the ballot campaigns for a $15 minimum wage and paid family and medical leave, had the opportunity to review the package and make recommendations. The "Grand Bargain" weakened the $15 minimum wage and paid leave proposals, and authorized the elimination of time-and-a-half on Sundays.
377.title: Preventing activists from weighing in on the "Grand Bargain" deal

383.description: Vote was on amending the underlying bill to allow for the abusive practice of “conversion therapy” via “talk therapy” aimed at coercing a change in an individual’s sexual orientation or gender identity.
383.title: Homophobia under the Guise of Free Speech

384.description: Vote was on prohibiting licensed mental health professionals from “practicing” on minors the damaging and homophobic/transphobic fraud of “conversion therapy,” which has the goal of “changing” a person’s sexual orientation or gender identity of a minor.
384.title: An Act relative to abusive practices to change sexual orientation and gender identity in minors (Conversion Therapy Ban)

387.description: Vote was on adopting Automatic Voter Registration, in which eligible voters who interface with the RMV or MassHealth would be automatically registered to vote unless they decline. With more than 700,000 eligible citizens in MA unregistered, AVR would increase the accuracy, security, and comprehensiveness of voter rolls.
387.title: An Act automatically registering voters and enhancing safeguards against fraud (AVR)

392.description: Vote was on creating a sales tax holiday in August 2018. Sales tax holidays are gimmicks that drain the state of much-needed revenue and do  not succeed at meaningfully boosting sales for small businesses.
392.title: Sales Tax Holiday

398.description: Vote was on sending to further study (i.e., tabling) an amendment to reinsert language giving physicians and other clinical professionals the  power to involuntarily hold, for 72 hours, individuals suffering from addiction. People who undergo involuntary treatment in Massachusetts are  twice as likely to die as people who undergo treatment voluntarily.
398.title: Further amendment: 72 Hour-Holds

408.description: Vote was on accepting the conference report version of the 2019 budget, which had stripped out vital protections for immigrant families (as found in Safe Communities Act (SCA))
408.title: On Acceptance of the Conference Report (FY 2019 Budget, without SCA provisions)

409.description: Vote was on repealing outdated and unconstitutional laws still on the books limiting reproductive rights. As the possibility of Roe v. Wade deterioration increases with each Trump Supreme Court appointee, it is more important than ever that state legislatures lead in protecting and advancing women’s reproductive rights.
409.title: An Act negating archaic statutes targeting young women (NASTY Women Act)

451.description: Vote was on overriding Republican Governor Charlie Baker’s veto of a bill requiring that the hiring, promotion and termination of employees in custodial, maintenance and other non-teaching positions in public schools be conducted in accordance with any governing collective bargaining agreement. Weakening unions is an important piece of our alarming, and growing, wealth and income inequality.
451.title: Override: An Act Relative to protecting the rights of custodial and other non-teaching employees of school districts

452.description: Vote was on creating a tax and regulatory framework for short-term rentals like Airbnb, which have exacerbated the affordable housing crisis by taking units off the market and turning them into investment properties.
452.title: An Act regulating and insuring short-term rentals (Conference Report)

458.description: Vote was to override Republican Governor Baker’s veto of language that would prevent his administration from effectively denying vulnerable children needed welfare benefits, by unilaterally counting a parent’s Social Security Income (afforded to disabled adults who are low-income) to determine children’s benefits eligibility.
458.title: TADFC Grant Payments

480.description: Vote was on a proposal from Republican Governor Charlie Baker to make the adoption of a more stringent calculation of benefits (counting a parent's Supplemental Security Income in determining their children's eligibility for welfare benefits) a precondition of lifting the punitive "cap on kids." Massachusetts is one of the only states that still denies benefits to children who were born while a family is receiving state assistance, and Baker's proposal sought to weaken the Legislature's effort to fix this.
480.title: Baker's punitive attack on low-income families

2.description: Vote was on giving pay increases to the Senate President, Speaker of the House, judges, the governor, and other constitutional officers; raising stipends to appointed committee chairs and select other legislative leaders; and increasing the number of legislators eligible for stipends. The bill would further centralize power in the already powerful House Speaker and create a more hierarchical and less democratic Legislature. The bill received little notice and no public hearing, and was fast-tracked while many vital priorities to the Commonwealth languish in perpetuity.
2.title: An Act Further Regulating the Compensation of Public Officials

33.description: Vote was on increasing the FY 2018 administrative budget of the Department of Environmental Protection by $1 million, from $25 million to $26 million (One of PM's budget asks).
33.title: Dept. of Environmental Protection Admin. (Redraft)

36.description: Vote was on increasing the FY 2018 budget of the Massachusetts Legal Assistance Corporation, which provides access to legal information, advice, and representation, for low-income MA residents by $2 million, from $18 million to $20 million (One of PM’s budget asks).
36.title: Masachusetts Legal Assitance Corporation

40.description: Vote was on establishing a schedule for implementing the 2015 recommendations of the Foundation Budget Review Commission. The FBRC found that the Commonwealth is underestimating the cost of K-12 education by $1-2 billion each year due to outdated assumptions regarding the costs of special education and closing the achievement gaps for low-income students and English Language Learners. (One of PM’s budget asks)
40.title: Foundation Budget Review Commission Recommendations

41.description: Vote was on eliminating the use of student standardized test performance in teacher evaluations. The use of student impact ratings in teacher evaluation ignores the many other factors, both individual and social, that affect a student’s performance, and creates problems in subjects where standardized tests are not given, such as in art, music, and gym.
41.title: Improving Overall Student Performance and Opportunity (Redraft)

47.description: Vote was on sending the Fair Share amendment, which would impose a 4% surtax on income above $1 million and allocate the revenue to a designated education and transportation fund, to the 2018 ballot.
47.title: Fair Share Amendment

52.description: Vote was on revising the language of Question 4 (marijuana legalization) while remaining faithful to its spirit. The bill contains language to promote economic opportunities in communities hurt by the drug war and to expunge the records of those convicted of offenses no longer deemed criminal, along with various further equity, educational, and environmental measures.
52.title: An Act to Ensure the Public Health and Safety of Patient and Consumer Access to Medical and Adult Use of Marijuana in the Commonwealth

54.description: The vote was on reducing the fine scale in the underlying bill, which created penalties for individuals who use their phones while driving, from $100-$250-$500 to $50-$100-$150.
54.title: Ensuring Fair Penalties

60.description: Vote was on the conference committee version of the Question 4 redraft (marijuana legalization), which remained faithful to the spirit of the original ballot initiative, while containing improvements in public health and social justice.
60.title: An Act to Ensure Safe Access to Marijuana

62.keyword: Health, LGBTQ, Public Education, Reproductive Rights
62.description: Vote was on requiring that sex education only be offered in schools on an elective basis, with written parent/guardian permission required for student participation
62.title: Opt In (An Act Relative to Health Youth)

66.keyword: Health, LGBTQ, Public Education, Reproductive Rights
66.description: Vote was on ensuring that a Massachusetts school electing to teach sex education uses a medically accurate, age-appropriate, and comprehensive curriculum. This would entail teaching students about the benefits of abstinence and delaying sex, building healthy relationships, consent, gender identity and sexual orientation, effective contraceptive use, and the prevention of pregnancy and sexually transmitted infections (STIs).
66.title: An Act Relative to Health Youth

68.description: Vote was on rejecting Governor Baker’s proposal to drop 100,000 low-income parents and 40,000 other adults off MassHealth, a proposal which would subject such individuals to higher premiums and a loss of dental coverage and other vital benefits.
68.title: An Act Furter Regulating Employer Contributions to Health Care

205.description: Vote was on lowering the felony larceny threshold in the bill from $1,500 to $1,000.
205.title: Property Crime Felony Threshold

206.description: Vote was on raising the fines in the bill associated with drunk driving, contradicting the bill's goal of reducing fees and fines.
206.title: Increased Penalties for Habitual Drunk Drivers

211.description: Vote was on establishing a new mandatory minimum for the crime of assaulting a police officer, which could have a chilling effect on protesters, especially ones of color.
211.title: Assault and Battery on a Police Officer

212.description: Vote was on allowing current prisoners serving mandatory minimum sentences for crimes for which mandatory minimums have been repealed to be eligible for good conduct credits earned on and after the effective date of the law.
212.title: Good Time Eligibility

213.description: Vote was on recriminalizing the act of disturbing a school assembly. The underlying bill established that it would no longer be an arrestable offense, allowing schools to handle discipline and seeking to curb the school-to-prison pipeline.
213.title: Disturbing a School Assembly

214.description: Vote was on establishing a new mandatory minimum for the crime of assaulting a police officer, which could have a chilling effect on protesters, especially ones of color. [Some members asked for a 2nd opportunity to vote]
214.title: Assault and Battery on a Police Officer

215.description: Vote was on reimposing mandatory minimums for low-level cocaine offenses, entrenching the failed model of the war on drugs which has played a significant role in mass incarceration.
215.title: Ensuring penalties for cocaine trafficing

217.description: Vote was on reimposing mandatory minimums for low-level cocaine offenses, entrenching the failed model of the war on drugs which has played a significant role in mass incarceration.
217.title: Retail drug offenses

218.description: Vote was on reimposing mandatory minimums related to selling drugs in school zones, entrenching the failed model of the war on drugs which has played a significant role in mass incarceration. "School zones" are a broad geographic determination, and most cases that fall into it have nothing to do with school children.
218.title: "Protecting" school zones

219.description: Vote was on striking a provision of the bill that would protect parents from being forced to testify against their children. The provision was a recognition that the parent/child relationship is one essential to well-being and warrants such testimonial privilege.
219.title: Parental testimony

222.description: Vote was on strengthening the mandatory minimums for fentanyl by reducing how many grams would trigger mandatory minimums, replacing “not more than 20 years” with “not less than 5 years,” and expanding its application to any Class A drug.
222.title: Fentanyl sentencing

223.description: Vote was on striking the provision of the bill that would raise the age of criminal majority from 18 to 19. The underlying bill sought to reduce recidivism among young adults and end the prison pipeline.
223.title: Juvenile age

225.description: Vote was on establishing a new mandatory minimum for carfentanil trafficking, doubling down on the policies that fueled mass incarceration.
225.title: Establishing Carfentanil Sentences

226.description: Vote was on requiring individuals in prison for a mandatory minimum sentence that has since been repealed to serve the full term of the sentence.
226.title: Serving term of incarceration

227.description: Vote was on expanding state wiretapping to enable prosecutors to use wiretapping to investigate low-level drug offenses not connected to organized crime or other conspiracies.
227.title: Expanding the wiretapping law

228.description: Vote was on allowing district attorneys to charge minors sharing sexually explicit images with a felony.
228.title: Making teen sexting a felony

229.description: Vote was on striking the provision that would allow for the sealing of convictions for resisting arrest.
229.title: Resisting arrest convictions

231.description: Vote was on enacting the Senate's comprehensive criminal justice reform bill.
231.title: An Act relative to criminal justice reform

266.description: Vote was on striking the provision of the underlying bill that instructs MassHealth to create a Medicaid buy-in plan for individuals or for employers whose workers qualify for MassHealth.
266.title: Eliminating the public option

271.description: Vote was on requiring health care providers to disclose the amount or charge for an admission, procedure, or service, including facility fees, to a patient or prospective patient in advance. [The amendment replaces the language in the underlying bill that makes such disclosure upon request only.]
271.title: Patient choice and protection

273.description: Vote was on requiring MassHealth to receive and review information from various state agencies at least once per month to determine whether any individuals receiving insurance via MassHealth may have a change in eligibility. The amendment would create unnecessary and costly bureaucracy for the sake of denying people access to health care.
273.title: Mass Health Eligibility

275.description: Vote was on eliminating the “name and shame list” from the underlying bill, an annual public report identifying the 50 Massachusetts employers with the highest number of employees who receive medical assistance, medical benefits, or assistance through the Health Safety Net Trust Fund.
275.title: Eliminating the "name and shame" list

277.description: Vote was on requiring the establishment of a “single payer benchmark” and annual reports detailing a comparison of the actual health care expenditures in the commonwealth for 2016, 2017 and 2018 with those under a single payer system. If the “single payer benchmark” outperforms actual costs, then the Health Policy Commission has to propose a single payer plan.
277.title: Health Care as a Right

279.description: Vote was on a comprehensive health care reform bill that, among other things, provided for a MassHealth "buy-in" option, the licensing of dental therapists to increase dental care, greater cost controls on prescription drugs and hospital bills, and increased funding for health and wellness programs.
279.title: HEALTH Act

335.description: Vote was on striking the section of the bill allowing juveniles ages 14-17 to receive adult criminal sentences for animal cruelty. Countless studies show that housing youths in adult prisons only worsens recidivism and works against a goal of rehabilitation.
335.title: Not Prosecuting Juveniles as Adults

342.description: Vote was on an attempt to nullify the proposed comprehensive civics education mandate by requiring a study on whether or not it is an "unfunded mandate" and then removing the mandate if it were deemed so.
342.title: Implementation Costs (Civics education)

343.description: Vote was on enacting a comprehensive civics education curriculum and requirement in schools across Massachusetts. Engaged and informed citizenship is essential component of a strong democracy.
343.title: An Act to promote and enhance civic engagement (Civics education)

350.description: Vote was on exempting units from the underlying tax on short-term rentals if they were rented for less than 21 days in a calendar year, thereby reducing the possible revenue the state could raise.
350.title: Exempted Lease Period

366.description: Vote was on establishing early voting for the 2018 primary elections. Early voting was a big success in 2016, and, it helps to eliminate unnecessary barriers to participating in elections.
366.title: Early Voting for the 2018 Primary Election

378.description: Vote was on updating the 25-year-old education funding formula that is costing schools at least $1 billion each year in aid, due to its outdated assumptions on the cost of health care, special education, ELL education, and closing the achievement gap.
378.title: An Act Modernizing the Foundation Budget for the 21st Century (FBRC)

381.description: Vote was on creating a surcharge for documentation at the Registries of Deeds to create a stronger and more stable funding source for the Community Preservation Act, which can be used for affordable housing, historic preservation, and green and open space.
381.title: Community Preservation Act

382.description: Vote was on creating a sales tax holiday in August 2018. Sales tax holidays are gimmicks that drain the state of much-needed revenue and do not succeed at meaningfully boosting sales for small businesses.
382.title: 2018 Sales Tax Holiday

394.keyword: Immigration, Civil Rights, Policing, Public Safety
394.description: Vote was on incorporating several key provisions of the Safe Communities Act (SCA) into the FY 2019 budget: (1) a prohibition on police inquiries about immigration status, a prohibition on certain collaboration agreements between local law enforcement and ICE, (3) a guarantee of basic due process protections, and (4) a prohibition on participation in a Muslim registry. The amendment upholds basic constitutional rights and would make communities safer.
394.title: Civil Rights and Safety (SCA provisions)

395.keyword: Immigration, Civil Rights, Policing, Public Safety
395.description: Vote was on a xenophobic amendment needlessly entangling police in deportations and set us back from the Lunn v. Commonwealth decision, which set limitations on such collaboration.
395.title: Promoting Discrimination

397.description: Vote was on a Republican messaging amendment to the budget to push racist welfare fraud myths and create burdens for small and minority-owned businesses.
397.title: Penalty for owner or operator for use of EBT at prohibited locations

411.description: Vote was on subjecting tax breaks for the biotech industry to periodic review to make sure that they are delivering the promised employment and public revenue promised.
411.title: Tax Expenditure Review

415.description: Vote was on reauthorizing a corporate tax giveaway for the biotech industry, including provisions increasing the amount of money available each year for industry tax incentives and thus draining much-needed revenue.
415.title: An Act providing continued investment in the life sciences industry in the Commonwealth

417.description: Vote was on an amendment to constrain the state from regulating vehicle emissions standards, ostensibly because doing so would place the state in violation of federal law. With the Trump administration day after day seeking to roll back critical environmental regulations, Massachusetts needs to be taking bolder action, not creating unnecessary, self-imposed constraints.
417.title: Constraining vehicle emissions regulation

425.description: Vote was on a strong and comprehensive climate mitigation and adaptation bill whose policies and programs will protect public health, increase the use of renewable energy, reduce greenhouse emissions, implement a price on carbon, and create jobs in the innovative green-energy economy. Given the rollbacks in climate policy occurring at the federal level, bold policy at the state level is vital.
425.title: An Act to promote a clean energy future

428.description: Vote was on empowering the AG’s office to prosecutes wage theft and holding businesses accountable for exploitative and illegal practices by their subcontractors to which they too often turn a blind eye.
428.title: An Act to prevent wage theft and promote employer accountability

429.description: Vote was on striking a central provision of the underlying bill (“We the People Act”), which seeks to curb the influence of money in politics. The 2010 Citizens United decision The provision calls for a limited constitutional convention focused on clarifying that the spending of money to influence elections is not protected free speech under the First Amendment and thereby enabling Congress and the states to better regulate political contributions.
429.title: Weakening the 'We the People Act'

432.description: Vote was on establishing a gender-neutral identity option for Massachusetts licenses, a recognition that some individuals may not identify as either male or female.
432.title: An Act relative to gender identity on Massachusetts identification

435.description: Vote was on creating a kind of court order (Extreme Risk Protection Order, or ERPO) to temporarily restrict a person's access to guns because they pose a significant danger to themselves or others, which can be requested by family members and law enforcement. Empowering family members, who are able to see early warning signs, to act in this way can prevent gun violence, whether mass shooting or suicide.
435.title: An Act relative to firearms (ERPO)

438.description: Vote was on adopting Automatic Voter Registration, in which eligible voters who interface with the RMV or MassHealth would be automatically registered to vote unless they decline. With more than 700,000 eligible citizens in MA unregistered, AVR would increase the accuracy, security, and comprehensiveness of voter rolls.
438.title: An Act automatically registering eligible voters and enhancing safeguards against fraud (AVR)

445.keyword: Immigration, Civil Rights, Policing, Public Safety
445.description: Vote was on accepting the conference report version of the 2019 budget, which had stripped out vital protections for immigrant families (as found in Safe Communities Act (SCA)) which had been passed by the MA Senate. Failure to include these SCA provisions in the budget was effectively the last opportunity for the MA Legislature to advance meaningful reforms and protections for immigrants in MA, who are under increasing threat from the Trump Administration’s baldly racist agenda.
445.title: On Acceptance of the Conference Report (FY 2019 Budget, without SCA provisions)

450.description: Vote was on amending the Community Benefit Districts bill to add protections for tenants in residential buildings proposed to be included in any community benefit district to make sure that the bill does not further worsen the eviction and affordable crisis faced by low- and middle-income communities in MA.
450.title: Tenants' Rights

451.description: Vote was on authorizing the creation of “Community Benefit District” (CBD) corporations, which could enable wealthy property owners to essentially “own” public spaces and impose fees on other property owners in the district with or without their approval, all with zero safeguards for civil liberties and equal access. This is part of a widespread and dangerous trend of degrading public spaces and turning them over to corporate control.
451.title: An Act Relative to Community Benefit Districts

460.description: Vote was on permitting judges to civilly commit individuals suffering from addiction to a treatment facility without a hearing, until the courts open, with the patient entitled to a hearing within 72 hours. People who undergo involuntary treatment in Massachusetts are twice as likely to die as people who undergo treatment voluntarily.
460.title: Alternative--and actually more dangerous--Pathways

463.description: Vote was on creating a sales tax holiday in August 2018. Sales tax holidays are gimmicks that drain the state of much-needed revenue and do not succeed at meaningfully boosting sales for small businesses.
463.title: Sales tax holiday

479.description: Vote was on enabling municipalities to place a question on the ballot to raise revenue for local and regional transportation projects. Many other states do this, and it provides communities a way to take action when inertia dominates in the State Legislature.
479.title: Regional Ballot Initiatives

488.description: Vote was on overriding Republican Governor Charlie Baker’s veto of a bill requiring that the hiring, promotion and termination of employees in custodial, maintenance and other non-teaching positions in public schools be conducted in accordance with any governing collective bargaining agreement. Weakening unions is an important piece of our alarming, and growing, wealth and income inequality.
488.title: Override: An Act relative to protecting the rights of custodial and other non-teaching employees of school districts

494.description: Vote was on creating a tax and regulatory framework for short-term rentals like Airbnb, which have exacerbated the affordable housing crisis by taking units off the market and turning them into investment properties.
494.title: An Act regulating and insuring short-term rentals

539.description: Vote was to override Republican Governor Baker’s veto of language that would prevent his administration from effectively denying vulnerable children needed welfare benefits, by unilaterally counting a parent’s Social Security Income (afforded to disabled adults who are low-income) to determine children’s benefits eligibility.
539.title: Veto Override: TAFDC Grant Payments

540.description: Vote was on a proposal from Republican Governor Charlie Baker to make the adoption of a more stringent calculation of benefits (counting a parent's Supplemental Security Income in determining their children's eligibility for welfare benefits) a precondition of lifting the punitive  "cap on kids." Massachusetts is one of the only states that still denies benefits to children who were born while a family is receiving state assistance, and Baker's proposal sought to weaken the Legislature's effort to fix this.
540.title: Baker's punitive attack on low-income families

H86.name: Proposal for a legislative amendment to the Constitution to provide resources for education and transportation through an additional tax on incomes in excess of one million dollars
H86.description: Creates a 4% surtax on income above $1 million to fund education and transportation reinvestment.

S16.name: Proposal for a legislative amendment to the Constitution to provide resources for education and transportation through an additional tax on incomes in excess of one million dollars
S16.description: Creates a 4% surtax on income above $1 million to fund education and transportation reinvestment.

H586.name: An Act providing rightful opportunities and meaningful investment for successful and equitable education
H586.description: Fixes our outdated school funding formula to more accurately and equitably distribute resources – giving all schools the funding they need to deliver high-quality education.

S238.name: An Act providing rightful opportunities and meaningful investment for successful and equitable education
S238.description: Fixes our outdated school funding formula to more accurately and equitably distribute resources – giving all schools the funding they need to deliver high-quality education.

H1221.name: An Act to guarantee debt-free public higher education
H1221.description: Creates a higher education system where every Massachusetts resident has a right to attend any public college or university free of tuition and fees.

S744.name: An Act to guarantee debt-free public higher education
S744.description: Creates a higher education system where every Massachusetts resident has a right to attend any public college or university free of tuition and fees.

H470.name: An Act relative to affordable and accessible high quality early education and care
H470.description: Makes high-quality early education and child care affordable and accessible to all Massachusetts families.

S288.name: An Act relative to affordable and accessible high quality early education and care
S288.description: Makes high-quality early education and child care affordable and accessible to all Massachusetts families.

H1194.name: An Act establishing Medicare for All in Massachusetts
H1194.description: Establishes a single payer system, in which the state provides health care to all residents as a right.

S683.name: An Act establishing Medicare for All in Massachusetts
S683.description: Establishes a single payer system, in which the state provides health care to all residents as a right.

H1769.name: An Act supporting affordable housing with a local option for a fee to be applied to certain real estate transactions
H1769.description: Enables cities and towns to assess a fee of 0.5-2% on residential and commercial real estate transactions, with the funds allocated to affordable housing trust funds.

S773.name: An Act supporting affordable housing with a local option for a fee to be applied to certain real estate transactions
S773.description: Enables cities and towns to assess a fee of 0.5-2% on residential and commercial real estate transactions, with the funds allocated to affordable housing trust funds.

H3573.name: An Act to protect the civil rights and safety of all Massachusetts residents
H3573.description: Limits local and state police collaboration with federal immigration agents, bars law enforcement and court personnel from inquiring about immigration status, and ensures due process protections.

S1401.name: An Act to protect the civil rights and safety of all Massachusetts residents
S1401.description: Limits local and state police collaboration with federal immigration agents, bars law enforcement and court personnel from inquiring about immigration status, and ensures due process protections.

H2047.name: An Act to strengthen inmate visitation
H2047.description: Strengthens and secures the rights of prisoners to receive visits and maintain relationships with their friends and loved ones without unnecessary interference from the state.

S1379.name: An Act to strengthen inmate visitation
S1379.description: Strengthens and secures the rights of prisoners to receive visits and maintain relationships with their friends and loved ones without unnecessary interference from the state.

H3566.name: An Act promoting housing opportunity and mobility through eviction sealing
H3566.description: Requires the sealing of eviction records in order to combat housing discrimination.

S824.name: An Act promoting housing opportunity and mobility through eviction sealing
S824.description: Requires the sealing of eviction records in order to combat housing discrimination.

H3320.name: An Act removing obstacles and expanding access to women's reproductive health
H3320.description: Reforms our state’s abortion laws so that every person can control their own body, life, and future.

S1209.name: An Act to remove obstacles and expand abortion access
S1209.description: Reforms our state’s abortion laws so that every person can control their own body, life, and future.

H685.name: An Act relative to election day registration
H685.description: Eliminates the arbitrary and discriminatory 20-day registration cutoff and allows eligible residents to register or re-register--and vote--at the polls on Election Day and during the early voting period.

S396.name: An Act relative to election day registration
S396.description: Eliminates the arbitrary and discriminatory 20-day registration cutoff and allows eligible residents to register or re-register--and vote--at the polls on Election Day and during the early voting period.

H719.name: An Act relative to ranked choice voting
H719.description: Adopts ranked choice voting for relevant elections, enabling voters to rank candidate preferences and ensuring that the ultimate winner commands a majority of support.

S414.name: An Act to use of ranked choice voting in elections
S414.description: Adopts ranked choice voting for relevant elections, enabling voters to rank candidate preferences and ensuring that the ultimate winner commands a majority of support.

H3572.name: An Act promoting equality and respect in the legislature
H3572.description: Creates an independent commission to investigate and report on complaints of workplace and sexual harassment in the Massachusetts Legislature.

S1898.name: An Act promoting equality and respect in the legislature
S1898.description: Creates an independent commission to investigate and report on complaints of workplace and sexual harassment in the Massachusetts Legislature.

H761.name: An Act relative to environmental justice and toxics reduction in the Commonwealth
H761.description: Codifies environmental justice into law and secures strong enforcement of the state’s current EJ policy.

S464.name: An Act relative to environmental justice and toxics reduction in the Commonwealth
S464.description: Codifies environmental justice into law and secures strong enforcement of the state’s current EJ policy.

H2836.name: An Act re-powering Massachusetts with 100 percent renewable energy
H2836.description: Sets the goal of 100% renewable energy economy-wide by 2045 and 100% renewable electricity by 2035.

S1958.name: An Act transitioning Massachusetts to 100 percent renewable energy
S1958.description: Sets the goal of 100% renewable energy economy-wide by 2045 and 100% renewable electricity by 2035.

H2810.name: An Act to promote green infrastructure, reduce greenhouse gas emissions, and create jobs
H2810.description: Sets a price on carbon emissions to incentivize the transition to renewable energy, with parts of the resulting revenue allocated for sustainable infrastructure.

S1924.name: An Act to Promote Green Infrastructure and Reduce Carbon Emissions
S1924.description: Sets a price on carbon emissions to incentivize the transition to renewable energy, with parts of the resulting revenue allocated for sustainable infrastructure.
